# Unprotected initializer in '__TokenRoles_init' function let any user call it and reinitialize the contract

# Lines of code

https://github.com/code-423n4/2024-08-chakra/blob/d0d45ae1d26ca1b87034e67180fac07ce9642fd9/solidity/handler/contracts/TokenRoles.sol#L19-L23


# Vulnerability details

## Impact

An unprotected initializer in the given function can have severe security implications. The '__TokenRoles_init' function is designed to initialize important roles in a smart contract, such as setting the owner and operator roles. 

However, if this function is left unprotected, any user can call it and reinitialize the contract, which leads to unauthorized role assignment, privilege escalation, or even loss of control.


## Proof of Concept

Unauthorized Role Assignment: Anyone can change the _owner and _operator by calling the initializer, effectively taking control of the contract. This means the attacker could assign themselves the admin or operator roles and have full control over the contract.

Privilege Escalation: Since _owner is granted the DEFAULT_ADMIN_ROLE, and _operator is given the OPERATOR_ROLE, an attacker could exploit this vulnerability to grant themselves administrative privileges, allowing them to make sensitive contract changes.

Loss of Control: If this initializer is called after the contract is already deployed and initialized by the legitimate owner, it could completely transfer control away from the intended contract owners, leading to irreversible damage.

Test

```solidity
// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT
pragma solidity ^0.8.24;

import "forge-std/Test.sol";
import "./TokenRoles.sol";

contract TokenRolesTest is Test {
    TokenRoles tokenRoles;
    address owner = address(0x1);
    address operator = address(0x2);
    address attacker = address(0x3);

    function setUp() public {
        tokenRoles = new TokenRoles();
        tokenRoles.__TokenRoles_init(owner, operator);
    }

    function testUnprotectedInitializer() public {
        // Attacker reinitializes the contract
        vm.prank(attacker);
        tokenRoles.__TokenRoles_init(attacker, attacker);

        // Check if attacker is now the owner and operator
        assertTrue(tokenRoles.hasRole(tokenRoles.DEFAULT_ADMIN_ROLE(), attacker));
        assertTrue(tokenRoles.is_operator(attacker));
    }
}
```

## Tools Used

Manual Review

## Recommended Mitigation Steps

To keep the initializer function safe, utilize the `initializer` modifier from OpenZeppelin's `Initializable` contract or implement a mechanism to ensure it is invoked only once. This approach mitigates reinitialization attacks and guarantees that only authorized entities can initialize the contract. 

Additionally, consider implementing access control measures, such as the `onlyOwner` modifier, to prevent unauthorized access.





## Assessed type

Access Control

# An attacker can steal ownership of implementation contracts `SettlementSignatureVerifier.sol` and `ERC20CodecV1.sol`

# Lines of code

https://github.com/code-423n4/2024-08-chakra/blob/main/solidity/handler/contracts/SettlementSignatureVerifier.sol#L10-L13
https://github.com/code-423n4/2024-08-chakra/blob/main/solidity/handler/contracts/ERC20CodecV1.sol#L5-L21


# Vulnerability details

## Impact
The contract inheriting UUPSUpgradeable.sol, namely; SettlementSignatureVerifier.sol is deployed using a proxy pattern whereby the implementation contract is used by the proxy contract for all its logic. 
In this pattern Proxycontract will make `delegatecall` to the implementation contract. In case of upgrading the contract in future it can be done by pointing the proxy contract to a new implementation contract. 

However, if the implementation contract is left uninitialized, it is possible for any user to gain ownership of the `onlyOwner` role in the implementation contract for SettlementSignatureVerifier.sol. Once the user has ownership they are able to perform an upgrade of the implementation contract's logic contract, and make all the authorized onlyOwner calls.

Due to this issue, an attacker can at any time (no front-run required) call `initialize()` directly on the implementation to steal ownership of the implementation contract.


## Proof of Concept
[This OZ's docs](https://docs.openzeppelin.com/upgrades-plugins/1.x/writing-upgradeable#initializing_the_implementation_contract) mentions the issue and it's mitigation needed to prevent the Upgradeable implementation contracts from this vulnerability.  

```solidity
....
import {OwnableUpgradeable} from "@openzeppelin/contracts-upgradeable/access/OwnableUpgradeable.sol";
import "@openzeppelin/contracts-upgradeable/proxy/utils/UUPSUpgradeable.sol";

contract SettlementSignatureVerifier is
    OwnableUpgradeable,
    UUPSUpgradeable,
    AccessControlUpgradeable
{
 .....
// no constructor having a call to _disableInitiailzers() can be found here in this implementation (logic) contract
 .....

    function initialize(
        address _owner,
        uint256 _required_validators
    ) public initializer {
        __Ownable_init(_owner);
        __UUPSUpgradeable_init();
        _grantRole(DEFAULT_ADMIN_ROLE, _owner);

        required_validators = _required_validators;
    }
 ....
```

## Tools Used
VS Code

## Recommended Mitigation Steps
Include the below snippet in the mentioned contract's code:

```solidity
/// @custom:oz-upgrades-unsafe-allow constructor
constructor() {
    _disableInitializers();
}
```
When initialize() gets called during deployment, that refers to the proxy contract. But when the implementation contract gets deployed constructor() gets called, hence _disableInitializers() in the constructor to disable initialize() on the implementation helps us in mitigating this issue.

Because it will update the storage value of `initialized = type(uint64).max` disallowing any direct initialize() calls on implementation contract, which can allow the caller to set themself as the owner and make the owner authorized calls, which were intended for the owner operating via proxy contract.

Some of the operations would be against the legit validators/managers which are among the core roles of protocol: 
1. `add_manager()`
2. `remove_manager()`








## Assessed type

Upgradable

# Default admin role not revoked on ownership transfer provides old owner address with same privileges

# Lines of code

https://github.com/code-423n4/2024-08-chakra/blob/d0d45ae1d26ca1b87034e67180fac07ce9642fd9/solidity/settlement/contracts/SettlementSignatureVerifier.sol#L64
https://github.com/code-423n4/2024-08-chakra/blob/d0d45ae1d26ca1b87034e67180fac07ce9642fd9/solidity/handler/contracts/SettlementSignatureVerifier.sol#L53
https://github.com/code-423n4/2024-08-chakra/blob/d0d45ae1d26ca1b87034e67180fac07ce9642fd9/solidity/settlement/contracts/BaseSettlement.sol#L64


# Vulnerability details

## Summary

**Context:**
In `handler/SettlementSignatureVerifier.sol`, `settlement/SettlementSignatureVerifier.sol` and `BaseSettlement.sol`, during initialization, the owner is provided with the DEFAULT_ADMIN_ROLE. In these contracts, the owner has the ability to call the add_manager()/remove_manager() functions to add/remove managers. These functions are restricted to the owner by the onlyOwner modifier. 

**Issue:**
The issue is that if the ownership is transferred to another owner, the DEFAULT_ADMIN_ROLE is not revoked from the old owner.

**Impact:**
Due to this, the old owner has access to call the public grantRole()/revokeRole() functions inherited from the AccessControlUpgradeable.sol contract. This is a privilege escalation issue since the old owner still has access to the roles management after being considered non-privileged in the system.

## Proof of Concept

1. In the initialize() function of the three respective contracts ([1](https://github.com/code-423n4/2024-08-chakra/blob/d0d45ae1d26ca1b87034e67180fac07ce9642fd9/solidity/settlement/contracts/BaseSettlement.sol#L64), [2](https://github.com/code-423n4/2024-08-chakra/blob/d0d45ae1d26ca1b87034e67180fac07ce9642fd9/solidity/settlement/contracts/SettlementSignatureVerifier.sol#L64), [3](https://github.com/code-423n4/2024-08-chakra/blob/d0d45ae1d26ca1b87034e67180fac07ce9642fd9/solidity/handler/contracts/SettlementSignatureVerifier.sol#L53)), we can see that the owner is provided with the DEFAULT_ADMIN_ROLE.

```solidity
        _grantRole(DEFAULT_ADMIN_ROLE, _owner);
```

2. In the add_manager()/remove_manager() function of the three respective contract ([1](https://github.com/code-423n4/2024-08-chakra/blob/d0d45ae1d26ca1b87034e67180fac07ce9642fd9/solidity/settlement/contracts/BaseSettlement.sol#L149C1-L162C6), [2](https://github.com/code-423n4/2024-08-chakra/blob/d0d45ae1d26ca1b87034e67180fac07ce9642fd9/solidity/settlement/contracts/SettlementSignatureVerifier.sol#L83C3-L96C6), [3](https://github.com/code-423n4/2024-08-chakra/blob/d0d45ae1d26ca1b87034e67180fac07ce9642fd9/solidity/handler/contracts/SettlementSignatureVerifier.sol#L62C1-L70C6)), the MANAGER_ROLE can be granted to an address only by the current owner due to the onlyOwner modifier. 

```solidity
    function add_manager(address _manager) external onlyOwner {
        grantRole(MANAGER_ROLE, _manager);
        emit ManagerAdded(msg.sender, _manager);
    }

    function remove_manager(address _manager) external onlyOwner {
        revokeRole(MANAGER_ROLE, _manager);
        emit ManagerRemoved(msg.sender, _manager);
    }
```

3. Now let's say, the ownership of either of the three contracts is transferred from address(A) to address(B) using the transferOwnership() function from the inherited OwnableUpgradeable.sol contract. This means that now only address(B) should be having the privilege to call the add_manager()/remove_manager() functions while address(A) is considered to be removed from the privileged system.

```solidity
File: OwnableUpgradeable.sol
102:     function transferOwnership(address newOwner) public virtual onlyOwner {
103:         if (newOwner == address(0)) {
104:             revert OwnableInvalidOwner(address(0));
105:         }
106:         _transferOwnership(newOwner);
107:     }
```

4. But as we observed in step 1 above, due to the DEFAULT_ADMIN_ROLE not being revoked on ownership transfer, address(A) still has the same privileges. Although the old owner does not have access to the add_manager() and revoke_manager() functions that are only restricted to the current owner, the old owner does have access to the public grantRole()/revokeRole() functions from the inherited AccessControlUpgradeable.sol contract. 
 - The old owner can use this functionality to take over either of the three contracts (where the ownership transfer took place) and add/remove the critical MANAGER_ROLE addresses that handle addition/removal of validators and setting the required number of validators for the signature validation threshold. The old owner could provide itself or some other address the MANAGER_ROLE to cause harm. 
```solidity
    function grantRole(bytes32 role, address account) public virtual onlyRole(getRoleAdmin(role)) {
        _grantRole(role, account);
    }


    function revokeRole(bytes32 role, address account) public virtual onlyRole(getRoleAdmin(role)) {
        _revokeRole(role, account);
    }
```

5. Note that the ownership can be transferred for several reasons such as in case the address is compromised, becomes malicious or there has been a decision to simply make the address non-privileged (e.g. private key rotation as a security practice).

## Tools Used
Manual Review

## Recommended Mitigation Steps
Override the transferOwnership() function and revoke the DEFAULT_ADMIN_ROLE from the old owner and provide it to the new owner.

Another simple solution would be to use the [TokenRoles.sol](https://github.com/code-423n4/2024-08-chakra/blob/main/solidity/handler/contracts/TokenRoles.sol) contract but for the MANAGER_ROLE instead of the OPERATOR_ROLE. 


## Assessed type

Governance

# The required_validators check can be bypassed in the `SettlementSignatureVerifier` contract because neither the `verifyECDSA` nor the ChakraSettlement's functions check that signatures are unique

# Lines of code

https://github.com/code-423n4/2024-08-chakra/blob/d0d45ae1d26ca1b87034e67180fac07ce9642fd9/solidity/settlement/contracts/SettlementSignatureVerifier.sol#L186-L214
https://github.com/code-423n4/2024-08-chakra/blob/d0d45ae1d26ca1b87034e67180fac07ce9642fd9/solidity/handler/contracts/SettlementSignatureVerifier.sol#L108-L141
https://github.com/code-423n4/2024-08-chakra/blob/d0d45ae1d26ca1b87034e67180fac07ce9642fd9/solidity/settlement/contracts/ChakraSettlement.sol#L195


# Vulnerability details

## Impact
The `required_validators` check can be bypassed in the `SettlementSignatureVerifier` (leading to an exploit of both the `receive_cross_chain_msg` and the `receive_cross_chain_callback` functions of the `ChakraSettlement` contract).

This is due to the fact that the `SettlementSignatureVerifier`'s `verifyECDSA` function *nor any other `ChakraSettlement`'s functions utilizing the `verifyECDSA` and `verify` functions* check that the `signatures` array encoded in bytes contains  unique

That check is lacking there, and this allows for signature malleability, thus not only allowing to use the same signature multiple times, but also **inflating the count of validators who have confirmed a particular transaction's initiation or settlement**.

Although the OpenZeppelin's ECDSA library is used, it doesn't automatically prevent the reuse of the signature multiple times unless you implement a nonce tracking mechanism.

## In this vulnerabality, it's not the signature malleability and reuse that are the main culprit, but the fact that there's no check to verify that each `signatures` signature item is signed by a DISTINCT signer.

***Meaning that if at least one of the `validators` gets compromised (which I do believe is very likely eventually, as it is likely going to be a remote server), he will be able to act like if ALL OF THE VALIDATORS WERE COMPROMISED.***

## Proof of Concept
You can see what the `required_validators` variable is intended to be used for:
```solidity
    function set_required_validators_num(
        uint256 _required_validators
    ) external virtual onlyRole(MANAGER_ROLE) {
        uint256 old = required_validators;
        required_validators = _required_validators;
        emit RequiredValidatorsChanged(msg.sender, old, required_validators);
    }
```

#### `required_validators` is the threshold number of validators that are required to sign the transaction in order for it to be valid, and it is configured at the `SettlementSignatureVerifier` level.

**This check is absolutely crucial to protect the protocol in case one of the whitelisted verifier's private key becomes compromised, because exploiting that validator's private key will not lead to any significant consequences.**

**That is due to the fact that, in order to really exploit the whitelisted validators collective signatures array, the attacker would need to compromise private keys of all of the validators for their total count to match `required_validators`.**

### Usually `required_validators` is set to 10 or more validators count threshold.

```solidity
    function view_required_validators_num() external view returns (uint256) {
        return required_validators;
    }
```

It is evident that there's currently no mechanism to prevent a "duplicate VALIDATOR" or "duplicate signature" attack:
```solidity
