# Due to missing whenNotPaused modifiers on "borrow" and "repay" CDPVault's functions, users can borrow and repay despite of emergency conditions being set-up by the PAUSER role

# Lines of code

https://github.com/code-423n4/2024-07-loopfi/blob/57871f64bdea450c1f04c9a53dc1a78223719164/src/CDPVault.sol#L256
https://github.com/code-423n4/2024-07-loopfi/blob/57871f64bdea450c1f04c9a53dc1a78223719164/src/CDPVault.sol#L272


# Vulnerability details

## Impact
Because of to missing whenNotPaused modifiers on `borrow` and `repay` `CDPVault`'s functions, users can borrow and repay, in spite of emergency conditions being set-up by the `PAUSER` role.

That leads to violating the rights of emergency-induced pausing coverage, during which the core functions should not be accessible.

## Oftentimes, the conditions convincing the `PAUSER` role to disable the `CDPVault` by `pause`ing it (reasons for enabling the emergency mode) are either one of the following situations:
1. A vulnerability in the contract/system was detected;
2. There was a ridiculous depeg of the underlying tokens' prices or other problems with oracles' trustiness.

For safety, both the `borrow` and `repay` features should be unavailable for callers when the `CDPVault` contract is paused.

Although both the `deposit` and `withdraw` functions have the `whenNotPaused` modifier attached to them, the `borrow` and `repay` functions lack attachment of proper modifiers.

The availability of repayment and borrowing features can lead to problems if abused under critical circumstances.

The inability to pause and temporarily prohibit the use of `repay` and `borrow` functions is especially crucial if the `CDPVault` contract gets paused because of  market conditions (e.g. various depegs). 

## Proof of Concept

As you can see from the code, unlike
```solidity
    function withdraw(address to, uint256 amount) external whenNotPaused
```
and
```solidity
    function deposit(address to, uint256 amount) external whenNotPaused
```
functions, the `borrow` and `repay` functions have the `whenNotPaused` modifier missing to be applied to them: 
```solidity
    /// @notice Borrows credit against collateral
    /// @param borrower Address of the borrower
    /// @param position Address of the position
    /// @param amount Amount of debt to generate [wad]
    /// @dev The borrower will receive the amount of credit in the underlying token
    function borrow(address borrower, address position, uint256 amount) external {
        int256 deltaDebt = toInt256(amount);
        modifyCollateralAndDebt({
            owner: position,
            collateralizer: position,
            creditor: borrower,
            deltaCollateral: 0,
            deltaDebt: deltaDebt
        });
    }

    /// @notice Repays credit against collateral
    /// @param borrower Address of the borrower
    /// @param position Address of the position
    /// @param amount Amount of debt to repay [wad]
    /// @dev The borrower will repay the amount of credit in the underlying token
    function repay(address borrower, address position, uint256 amount) external {
        int256 deltaDebt = -toInt256(amount);
        modifyCollateralAndDebt({
            owner: position,
            collateralizer: position,
            creditor: borrower,
            deltaCollateral: 0,
            deltaDebt: deltaDebt
        });
    }
```


I know that historically some of submissions that cover the missing `whenNotPaused` modifier vulnerability are sometimes donwgraded to being "QA" or "Low-severity", but I believe that having pausing control of availability of `repay` and `borrow` features is critical, because if there're for instance serious market problems or rapid depegs, the `CDPPool` is at risk of becoming insolvent, calculations can be inflated.

#### And potential attack vectors can be also identified later, which, if leak into publicity, in the absence of ability to correctly pause the full `CDPVault` contract, can expose the `CDPVault` contract to the risk of getting robbed.

Here're some examples of "missing `whenNotPaused` modifier" submissions that were accepted as "Medium-severity" on Code4rena, to back up my point of view:
- https://github.com/code-423n4/2022-06-connext-findings/issues/175;
- https://github.com/code-423n4/2023-07-lens-findings/issues/108;

## Tools Used
Manual review.

## Recommended Mitigation Steps
As the protocol doesn't explicitly state that it's absolutely permissionless (like, for instance, Balancer), and other core functions are unavailable during the contract pausing (freezing) periods, it's highly recommended to append the `whenNotPaused` modifiers to the `repay` and `borrow` functions likewise. E.g.:
```diff
-   function borrow(address borrower, address position, uint256 amount) external
+   function borrow(address borrower, address position, uint256 amount) external whenNotPaused
{
        int256 deltaDebt = toInt256(amount);
        modifyCollateralAndDebt({
            owner: position,
            collateralizer: position,
            creditor: borrower,
            deltaCollateral: 0,
            deltaDebt: deltaDebt
        });
    }

    /// @notice Repays credit against collateral
    /// @param borrower Address of the borrower
    /// @param position Address of the position
    /// @param amount Amount of debt to repay [wad]
    /// @dev The borrower will repay the amount of credit in the underlying token
-   function repay(address borrower, address position, uint256 amount) external {
+   function repay(address borrower, address position, uint256 amount) external whenNotPaused {

        int256 deltaDebt = -toInt256(amount);
        modifyCollateralAndDebt({
            owner: position,
            collateralizer: position,
            creditor: borrower,
            deltaCollateral: 0,
            deltaDebt: deltaDebt
        });
    }
```


